Invoking: `validate` with `{'patch': '--- a/Modules/_cursesmodule.c
+++ b/Modules/_cursesmodule.c
@@ -255,7 +255,7 @@ _curses_initscr_impl(PyObject *module)
     PyCursesWindowObject *winobj;

     if (initialised) {
-        wrefresh(stdscr);
+        if (!isendwin()) wrefresh(stdscr);
         return (PyObject *)PyCursesWindow_New(stdscr, NULL);
     }
 '}`
responded: Now I have all the information I need. The issue is that in `_curses_initscr_impl`, when `initialised` is TRUE, it calls `wrefresh(stdscr)` without checking if `endwin()` has been called. After `endwin()` is called, `stdscr` becomes invalid, but `initialised` remains TRUE.

The fix is to check if `endwin()` has been called using the `isendwin()` function. If it has been called, we should reinitialize the curses library instead of trying to refresh an invalid `stdscr`.

Here's my proposed fix:

args.patch:
diff --git a/Modules/_cursesmodule.c b/Modules/_cursesmodule.c
index d32cff66144..ca678e848d7 100644
--- a/Modules/_cursesmodule.c
+++ b/Modules/_cursesmodule.c
@@ -3255,7 +3255,7 @@ _curses_initscr_impl(PyObject *module)
     PyCursesWindowObject *winobj;

     if (initialised) {
-        wrefresh(stdscr);
+        if (!isendwin()) wrefresh(stdscr);
         return (PyObject *)PyCursesWindow_New(stdscr, NULL);
     }

